{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3db92743-2250-4b2c-afff-3c21cf75d9f2","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from your .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n**1. Exec into the container:**\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install the diagnostics tool:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace (30 seconds):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the trace file off the container:**\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** the `.nettrace` file in Visual Studio (Diagnostics Hub), PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available, copy the `dotnet-trace` standalone from a build or use `perfcollect` alternatives.\n- For more detail, add `--providers Microsoft-DotNETCore-SampleProfiler` explicitly.\n- If you can't install tools in the container image, consider adding them to your Dockerfile or using a sidecar with shared process namespace (`shareProcessNamespace: true` in your pod spec).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"53e57a56-e61a-419b-9bbb-31b28c63e002","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to collect a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. They have admin access on the host.\n\nThis is a knowledge/guidance question - I don't need to search a codebase or run commands. I can provide the answer directly based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics tools.\n\nFor .NET diagnostics in Windows containers on Kubernetes, the key approaches are:\n\n1. **dotnet-trace** - the cross-platform .NET tracing tool\n2. **dotnet-counters** - for real-time monitoring\n3. **PerfView** - Windows-specific, more powerful\n\n\nSince they're in a Windows container with admin access, the most practical path is to exec into the container, install the dotnet-trace tool, and collect a trace directly from the running process.","outputTokens":585,"requestId":"680E:147218:C42A80:D15963:6A0B0026"},"id":"fdd3b8f1-9662-45b5-b52f-df13c839d680","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:04:03.635Z","parentId":"30d38aed-58cb-42e2-a7ae-248de2d50e99"}
